1
00:00:02,721 --> 00:00:06,481
(children chattering and screaming)

2
00:00:06,481 --> 00:00:08,961
- There's (murmuring)

3
00:00:08,961 --> 00:00:12,561
(children chattering and screaming)

4
00:00:12,561 --> 00:00:13,641
- Look at those, cool.

5
00:00:13,641 --> 00:00:16,801
- [Narrator] This was no
ordinary outing to the zoo.

6
00:00:16,801 --> 00:00:18,881
It was a very special occasion.

7
00:00:20,041 --> 00:00:22,321
It was part of a programme filmed in 1964

8
00:00:22,321 --> 00:00:25,161
when we brought together a group of seven-year-old children

9
00:00:25,161 --> 00:00:27,121
from vastly different backgrounds.

10
00:00:28,841 --> 00:00:29,681
(children screaming)

11
00:00:29,681 --> 00:00:31,561
We went to prep schools, primary schools,

12
00:00:31,561 --> 00:00:33,721
state schools, and private schools

13
00:00:33,721 --> 00:00:35,521
and picked out 14 children.

14
00:00:37,201 --> 00:00:38,681
We brought them together because we wanted

15
00:00:38,681 --> 00:00:40,921
a glimpse of the shop steward and the executive

16
00:00:40,921 --> 00:00:42,161
of the year 2000.

17
00:00:43,761 --> 00:00:45,961
"Give me a child until he is seven,

18
00:00:45,961 --> 00:00:47,721
"and I will give you the man."

19
00:00:49,441 --> 00:00:51,321
These children are now 14,

20
00:00:51,321 --> 00:00:54,281
halfway between childhood and manhood.

21
00:00:54,281 --> 00:00:56,401
This is our interim report.

22
00:00:57,241 --> 00:01:01,681
- If we did all love Jeffrey and we all want to marry.

23
00:01:01,681 --> 00:01:02,481
- Yeah.

24
00:01:02,481 --> 00:01:05,401
- I think I know the one that he'd likes best,

25
00:01:05,401 --> 00:01:07,401
and that's her.

26
00:01:07,401 --> 00:01:09,281
- [Narrator] Jackie, Lindsay, Susan.

27
00:01:10,281 --> 00:01:12,001
- Plenty of boyfriends, but not one--

28
00:01:12,001 --> 00:01:13,761
- Not one in particular.

29
00:01:13,761 --> 00:01:15,401
You're friends with
plenty of boys, you know.

30
00:01:16,441 --> 00:01:19,601
- My heart's desire is to see my daddy,

31
00:01:19,601 --> 00:01:21,601
who's 6000 miles away.

32
00:01:21,601 --> 00:01:22,441
- [Narrator] Bruce.

33
00:01:22,441 --> 00:01:23,881
- You know, I've been getting on well

34
00:01:23,881 --> 00:01:28,881
with my stepfather, and I like to see my father occasionally

35
00:01:28,961 --> 00:01:31,801
and he does come over from Rhodesia.

36
00:01:31,801 --> 00:01:33,481
- [Interviewer] Do you have a girlfriend?

37
00:01:33,481 --> 00:01:35,481
- [Narrator] Nicholas
from the Yorkshire Dales.

38
00:01:37,281 --> 00:01:40,441
- (chuckling) I don't want to answer that.

39
00:01:40,441 --> 00:01:44,641
I don't answer those kind of questions.

40
00:01:44,641 --> 00:01:46,921
No, I'm not answering that one.

41
00:01:47,961 --> 00:01:51,041
(gentle piano music)

42
00:01:52,561 --> 00:01:54,041
- [Narrator] Suzy.

43
00:01:54,041 --> 00:01:56,201
- I gave that up as a failure.

44
00:01:56,201 --> 00:01:57,721
- I was gonna be a policeman,

45
00:01:57,721 --> 00:02:01,521
but I've thought how hard
it would be to join in.

46
00:02:01,521 --> 00:02:02,361
- [Narrator] Paul.

47
00:02:02,361 --> 00:02:04,481
- Basketball appeals to me most,

48
00:02:04,481 --> 00:02:08,401
but with this school, I'm
one of their best players

49
00:02:08,401 --> 00:02:11,601
in form two, but when I get into a team,

50
00:02:11,601 --> 00:02:13,881
they make me look like I can't play.

51
00:02:13,881 --> 00:02:18,881
- I feel like bundling when
there's already a fight.

52
00:02:19,641 --> 00:02:21,281
- I was gonna be a film star, but--

53
00:02:21,281 --> 00:02:22,121
- [Narrator] Symon.

54
00:02:22,121 --> 00:02:26,241
- Now, I'm gonna be an
electrical engineer,

55
00:02:26,241 --> 00:02:28,601
which is more to reality really.

56
00:02:28,601 --> 00:02:33,361
(children singing in a foreign language)

57
00:02:34,961 --> 00:02:36,841
- [Narrator] Singing
Waltzing Matilda in Latin

58
00:02:36,841 --> 00:02:39,681
at an exclusive pre-prep
school in Kensington,

59
00:02:39,681 --> 00:02:41,081
we chose three boys.

60
00:02:43,081 --> 00:02:43,921
Charles,

61
00:02:46,001 --> 00:02:46,801
Andrew.

62
00:02:48,081 --> 00:02:50,161
- I read the Financial Times.

63
00:02:50,161 --> 00:02:51,161
- [Narrator] And John.

64
00:02:51,161 --> 00:02:53,881
- I read Observer and the Times.

65
00:02:53,881 --> 00:02:56,201
- What do you like about it?

66
00:02:56,201 --> 00:02:59,281
- Well, I like, I usually
look at the headlines,

67
00:02:59,281 --> 00:03:03,481
and then read about them, about it.

68
00:03:04,921 --> 00:03:07,961
- I like my newspaper because I got shares

69
00:03:07,961 --> 00:03:11,521
and I know every day what the shares are.

70
00:03:11,521 --> 00:03:12,561
- Stuff like misers like you like.

71
00:03:12,561 --> 00:03:13,841
(Andrew laughing)

72
00:03:13,841 --> 00:03:16,801
- No, but on Mondays, they don't move up,

73
00:03:16,801 --> 00:03:18,201
so I don't look at it.

74
00:03:18,201 --> 00:03:21,721
I made several blunders on Seven Up.

75
00:03:21,721 --> 00:03:23,961
For instance, I said I
was going to Trinity Hall

76
00:03:23,961 --> 00:03:25,761
instead of Trinity College.

77
00:03:25,761 --> 00:03:28,281
They didn't like that too
much, nor did my father.

78
00:03:29,121 --> 00:03:31,561
Also, I rather exaggerated when I said

79
00:03:31,561 --> 00:03:34,681
how much I liked stocks and shares

80
00:03:34,681 --> 00:03:36,561
because I don't anymore.

81
00:03:36,561 --> 00:03:38,041
- [Interviewer] How do
you think you've changed

82
00:03:38,041 --> 00:03:40,561
since you were seven years old?

83
00:03:40,561 --> 00:03:42,681
- Well, I mean, one grows so slowly

84
00:03:42,681 --> 00:03:45,561
that one never notices honestly.

85
00:03:45,561 --> 00:03:48,841
I feel the same as I felt
at seven, I may not be.

86
00:03:48,841 --> 00:03:50,801
When I leave this school,

87
00:03:50,801 --> 00:03:54,001
I'm going to Collet Court,

88
00:03:56,641 --> 00:03:59,401
and then I will be going to
Westminster Boarding School

89
00:03:59,401 --> 00:04:00,721
if I pass the exam.

90
00:04:00,721 --> 00:04:02,241
- [Narrator] John passed
the entrance exam,

91
00:04:02,241 --> 00:04:04,761
and is a weekly boarder
at Westminster School.

92
00:04:04,761 --> 00:04:06,441
- When I leave school,

93
00:04:06,441 --> 00:04:10,561
I'm going the Dragon School, I might,

94
00:04:10,561 --> 00:04:14,001
and mummy's, and after I might go

95
00:04:14,001 --> 00:04:17,001
to Charter House Marlborough.

96
00:04:17,001 --> 00:04:18,841
- [Narrator] Charles is at Marlborough.

97
00:04:18,841 --> 00:04:20,161
- When I leave this school,

98
00:04:20,161 --> 00:04:23,721
I go to Broadstairs' St. Peter's Court,

99
00:04:24,761 --> 00:04:28,081
then after that, I'm
going to Charterhouse.

100
00:04:29,241 --> 00:04:31,561
- [Narrator] Andrew is at Charterhouse.

101
00:04:31,561 --> 00:04:33,441
- When I leave this school,

102
00:04:33,441 --> 00:04:37,681
I'm down for Heathfield
and Southover Manor.

103
00:04:37,681 --> 00:04:39,721
- [Narrator] Suzy is at Southover Manor.

104
00:04:40,601 --> 00:04:42,401
- [Teacher] Would everybody
please sit round now?

105
00:04:42,401 --> 00:04:43,481
- [Narrator] For
one-third of our children,

106
00:04:43,481 --> 00:04:46,761
their education was
pre-planned and paid for.

107
00:04:46,761 --> 00:04:48,481
The remainder went to state schools,

108
00:04:48,481 --> 00:04:51,001
and their future seemed less certain.

109
00:04:51,001 --> 00:04:52,761
- I want to be a jockey when I grow up.

110
00:04:52,761 --> 00:04:56,921
Yeah, I want to be a
jockey when I grow up.

111
00:04:57,961 --> 00:05:00,881
(horse hooves clipping)

112
00:05:00,881 --> 00:05:03,681
- [Narrator] Tony is on the
way to achieving his ambition.

113
00:05:03,681 --> 00:05:05,161
He spends all his free time

114
00:05:05,161 --> 00:05:07,681
at Tommy Gosling's
Racing Stables at Epsom.

115
00:05:09,281 --> 00:05:11,841
- [Tony] My dad got on to Mr. Gosling.

116
00:05:11,841 --> 00:05:13,561
Mr. Gosling told me I can come here

117
00:05:13,561 --> 00:05:16,721
for every school holidays
and learn a bit more.

118
00:05:16,721 --> 00:05:20,201
(horse hooves thundering)

119
00:05:22,561 --> 00:05:24,001
Next April, I'll be leaving school,

120
00:05:24,001 --> 00:05:25,561
and I'll work for him for good.

121
00:05:32,641 --> 00:05:34,801
- [Interviewer] Did your parents
encourage you to do this?

122
00:05:34,801 --> 00:05:36,841
- Yeah, they're pleased with
everything what I've got,

123
00:05:36,841 --> 00:05:38,041
you know, going to do,

124
00:05:39,641 --> 00:05:42,201
but they always has
wanted me to be a jockey.

125
00:05:43,361 --> 00:05:44,361
- [Interviewer] Why?

126
00:05:45,441 --> 00:05:49,041
- Enjoyment, just to
say, "My son's a jockey,"

127
00:05:49,041 --> 00:05:49,881
like, you know what I mean?

128
00:05:50,841 --> 00:05:51,641
(children singing)

129
00:05:51,641 --> 00:05:52,761
- [Narrator] Tony's change
from elementary school

130
00:05:52,761 --> 00:05:55,001
to Secondary Modern
didn't alter his ambition,

131
00:05:55,001 --> 00:05:57,441
but how about the other children?

132
00:05:57,441 --> 00:06:00,121
Has a change of school changed them?

133
00:06:00,121 --> 00:06:01,721
(children chanting)

134
00:06:01,721 --> 00:06:05,881
Bruce was at a pre-preparatory
boarding school in Surrey.

135
00:06:07,441 --> 00:06:11,281
- And that's farmer heath
gives me nightmares.

136
00:06:12,401 --> 00:06:14,321
I was about five when I went there,

137
00:06:15,241 --> 00:06:16,841
and then,
(child yelling)

138
00:06:16,841 --> 00:06:19,681
I suppose I was too young
really to understand it,

139
00:06:19,681 --> 00:06:21,001
and I thought it was a
bit severe at the time,

140
00:06:21,001 --> 00:06:23,121
but then I just got used to it,

141
00:06:23,121 --> 00:06:25,081
and didn't have sort of any impulses

142
00:06:25,081 --> 00:06:27,361
to do things wrong, anything like that,

143
00:06:27,361 --> 00:06:30,321
and I just got into the track of.

144
00:06:30,321 --> 00:06:31,521
- [Boy] We're supposed to go sideways.

145
00:06:31,521 --> 00:06:33,081
- [Bruce] You know, of what they said

146
00:06:33,081 --> 00:06:34,881
you must do and mustn't.

147
00:06:34,881 --> 00:06:37,721
- Right, steady.

148
00:06:37,721 --> 00:06:40,641
Let's go left foot everyone, place.

149
00:06:41,681 --> 00:06:42,921
Squad pleasing.

150
00:06:45,481 --> 00:06:49,201
- At St. Paul's, I like the companionship,

151
00:06:49,201 --> 00:06:52,321
you know, with other boys really.

152
00:06:53,561 --> 00:06:56,761
It's a bit, and you get that
much more in a boarding school.

153
00:06:56,761 --> 00:07:00,401
- Well, I think boarding
makes you feel self-sufficient

154
00:07:02,321 --> 00:07:04,841
and also teaches you to
be away from your parents,

155
00:07:04,841 --> 00:07:08,561
and to live with people for a long time,

156
00:07:08,561 --> 00:07:10,641
which you have to do in later life anyway.

157
00:07:12,321 --> 00:07:14,241
- Well, I agree with
that a certain amount,

158
00:07:14,241 --> 00:07:17,161
but when you board on a weekly basis,

159
00:07:17,161 --> 00:07:19,881
you have the best of
both worlds, so to speak.

160
00:07:21,121 --> 00:07:23,721
One sees one's parents at the weekend,

161
00:07:23,721 --> 00:07:25,641
and one gets all the benefits

162
00:07:25,641 --> 00:07:27,361
from an English boarding school.

163
00:07:28,321 --> 00:07:31,041
- I think prep school
boarding is a bad idea

164
00:07:31,041 --> 00:07:35,001
because up til about 12,

165
00:07:36,121 --> 00:07:38,081
maybe it's different with other people,

166
00:07:38,081 --> 00:07:41,761
but I've found you're much
more attached to your parents

167
00:07:41,761 --> 00:07:44,681
once you come to about 13, 14,

168
00:07:46,441 --> 00:07:48,401
you're not quite so attached to them.

169
00:07:48,401 --> 00:07:50,201
- [Narrator] Two of our boys
who didn't have the chance

170
00:07:50,201 --> 00:07:51,801
to be attached to their parents

171
00:07:51,801 --> 00:07:53,361
were those brought up in a children's home

172
00:07:53,361 --> 00:07:56,641
supported by charity, Symon.

173
00:07:56,641 --> 00:07:57,761
- I had one dream,

174
00:07:58,681 --> 00:08:01,001
and everything flew up in the air.

175
00:08:01,001 --> 00:08:03,041
It all landed on my head.

176
00:08:04,601 --> 00:08:06,521
- [Narrator] Symon stayed at
the home until last Christmas

177
00:08:06,521 --> 00:08:08,841
when he returned to live with his mother.

178
00:08:08,841 --> 00:08:11,441
- They say, "Where's your father, then?

179
00:08:11,441 --> 00:08:13,481
"You know, when your mum's out at work,

180
00:08:13,481 --> 00:08:15,161
"stay with your father."

181
00:08:15,161 --> 00:08:17,081
And I just tell them, I ain't got one.

182
00:08:22,601 --> 00:08:24,801
- [Interviewer] What
effect has that had on you?

183
00:08:26,281 --> 00:08:28,481
- Well, I don't think
it's had any effect on me

184
00:08:28,481 --> 00:08:33,481
because what you don't
have, you don't miss,

185
00:08:35,321 --> 00:08:36,961
as far as I can see.

186
00:08:36,961 --> 00:08:38,161
- [Narrator] Also at the children's home

187
00:08:38,161 --> 00:08:40,321
with Symon was Paul.
(children singing)

188
00:08:40,321 --> 00:08:43,201
He and his family emigrated
when he was eight.

189
00:08:43,201 --> 00:08:45,521
- I don't like the big boys hitting us

190
00:08:45,521 --> 00:08:49,041
and the monitors up in the washroom

191
00:08:49,041 --> 00:08:50,921
sends the nurse out,

192
00:08:50,921 --> 00:08:53,961
and there's no talking,
but I wasn't talking today,

193
00:08:53,961 --> 00:08:57,201
and Brown sent me out for nothing.

194
00:08:57,201 --> 00:08:59,601
- [Interviewer] What do
you remember of England?

195
00:09:01,401 --> 00:09:03,521
- It seemed to be raining all the time.

196
00:09:03,521 --> 00:09:05,641
I wouldn't stake my life on it

197
00:09:05,641 --> 00:09:07,921
because I can't remember very much.

198
00:09:07,921 --> 00:09:09,761
- [Narrator] He went to Australia

199
00:09:09,761 --> 00:09:10,761
to start a new life.

200
00:09:11,921 --> 00:09:15,641
- [Paul] Well, I was going
to become a bank accountant,

201
00:09:15,641 --> 00:09:18,961
but it's more book taking, the mess,

202
00:09:18,961 --> 00:09:21,001
and that was main reason I was thinking

203
00:09:21,001 --> 00:09:23,481
about becoming a panel beater.

204
00:09:24,841 --> 00:09:29,841
And I don't know why now I've
stopped thinking about that.

205
00:09:30,241 --> 00:09:32,161
I just haven't made up my mind yet.

206
00:09:32,161 --> 00:09:34,441
I was going to be a phys ed teacher,

207
00:09:34,441 --> 00:09:35,761
but one of the teachers told me

208
00:09:35,761 --> 00:09:39,361
that they had to get up into university.

209
00:09:39,361 --> 00:09:40,201
- [Interviewer] Were you happy

210
00:09:40,201 --> 00:09:41,801
at the children's home in England?

211
00:09:42,801 --> 00:09:43,721
- I mean, I didn't mind that really

212
00:09:43,721 --> 00:09:46,281
because we didn't know what was going on

213
00:09:46,281 --> 00:09:47,361
because I was a bit young.

214
00:09:48,481 --> 00:09:49,561
(Symon coughing)

215
00:09:49,561 --> 00:09:50,401
- [Interviewer] Were you happier then

216
00:09:50,401 --> 00:09:51,801
than you are now?

217
00:09:54,441 --> 00:09:56,841
- In a way, yeah, I was,

218
00:09:56,841 --> 00:09:59,401
but then, I'm happy for being at home.

219
00:10:00,921 --> 00:10:02,321
At the school, everything you wanted,

220
00:10:02,321 --> 00:10:04,001
you just had it,

221
00:10:04,001 --> 00:10:05,441
and everybody was your friend,

222
00:10:06,321 --> 00:10:08,721
and you never knew any enemies, really,

223
00:10:08,721 --> 00:10:11,961
but here, people are undecided about you.

224
00:10:13,001 --> 00:10:14,401
They could be your friend one day,

225
00:10:14,401 --> 00:10:16,601
and not the next.

226
00:10:16,601 --> 00:10:19,641
- [Neil] And then I moved up
to a comprehensive school.

227
00:10:19,641 --> 00:10:22,281
I found it much bigger, of course,

228
00:10:22,281 --> 00:10:23,121
and I found it hard to
settle into at first.

229
00:10:23,121 --> 00:10:24,561
- [Narrator] From a Liverpool suburb,

230
00:10:24,561 --> 00:10:26,881
returning home from the
comprehensive school,

231
00:10:26,881 --> 00:10:28,401
Neil and Peter.

232
00:10:28,401 --> 00:10:29,361
- I'm much more happy here

233
00:10:29,361 --> 00:10:31,081
than when I first came.

234
00:10:31,081 --> 00:10:32,961
You get so many different types of people.

235
00:10:32,961 --> 00:10:35,521
People different sort of brains, you know,

236
00:10:35,521 --> 00:10:37,721
from the very clever people

237
00:10:37,721 --> 00:10:39,721
to you know, people who haven't got

238
00:10:39,721 --> 00:10:41,761
much sense at all really.

239
00:10:41,761 --> 00:10:43,641
Well, we pretend we've got swords,

240
00:10:43,641 --> 00:10:46,961
and we make the noise
of the swords fighting,

241
00:10:46,961 --> 00:10:51,041
and Lancelot he stabs
us, we go (groaning).

242
00:10:51,041 --> 00:10:51,881
I've been playing since I started

243
00:10:51,881 --> 00:10:54,321
at the comprehensive school
since the first year.

244
00:10:58,281 --> 00:11:00,121
We play international wrestling.

245
00:11:00,121 --> 00:11:02,601
- Yeah, that's only summer time, though.

246
00:11:02,601 --> 00:11:05,401
- Yeah, only when we can go in the grass.

247
00:11:05,401 --> 00:11:06,321
- There used to be a senior team,

248
00:11:06,321 --> 00:11:07,681
but they all lost interest.

249
00:11:10,401 --> 00:11:13,161
Watch this, checkmate.

250
00:11:15,481 --> 00:11:18,721
- Oh, hey, gosh, it is.

251
00:11:20,201 --> 00:11:21,241
How did you do that?

252
00:11:21,241 --> 00:11:22,921
I guess it's a very good
idea to have competition

253
00:11:22,921 --> 00:11:25,161
otherwise, you might start to relax really

254
00:11:25,161 --> 00:11:26,521
and not to try hard enough.

255
00:11:28,721 --> 00:11:30,521
- [Interviewer] What do you think?

256
